DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
"PGstandard.pl",
"MathObjects.pl",
"PGcourse.pl",
"parserPopUp.pl",
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");
Context()->variables->add(q=>'Real');

$x1 = random(90,110);
$y1 = random(25,35);

$x2 = random(190,210);
$y2 = random(20,24);

$q = random(90,120,1);

$int = random(1900,2100,10);
$perunit = random(5,10);

$rev = Compute("q*(($y2-$y1)/($x2-$x1)(q-$x1)+$y1)");
$cost = Compute("($int + q*$perunit)");
$fx = Compute("q*(($y2-$y1)/($x2-$x1)(q-$x1)+$y1) - ($int + q*$perunit)");

$ans = $fx->eval(q=>$q);


Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT

Express profit as a function of two quantity demand-price pairs, quantity, initial cost, and per-unit cost, assuming that demand price is a linear function, where the quantity demand-price pairs are \(($x1,$y1)\) and \(($x2,$y2)\) and the quantity is \($q\), the initial cost is $\($int\) and the per-unit cost is $\($perunit\). (You may find it useful to have intermediate computations that find the coefficients of the demand price function, and the demand price.)
$BR
\(Profit(q)=\)\{ans_rule(50)\}
$BR
\(Profit($q)=\)\{ans_rule\}

END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

ANS($fx->cmp());
ANS($ans->cmp());


Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_SOLUTION
${PAR}SOLUTION:${PAR}

\(revenue(q)=\left(\left(\frac{p2-p1}{q2-q1}\right)(q-q1)+p1\right)q\)
\(=\left(\left(\frac{$y2-$y1}{$x2-$x1}\right)(q-$x1)+$y1\right)q=$rev\)
$BR
$BR
\(cost(q)=initial\ cost+unit\ cost*q=$cost\)
$BR
\(profit(q)=revenue(q)-cost(q)\)
\(=\left(\left(\frac{p2-p1}{q2-q1}\right)(q-q1)+p1\right)q-(initial\ cost+unit\ cost*q)\)
$BR
\(=$fx\)
$BR
\(profit($q)=$ans\)

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

COMMENT('MathObject version.');

ENDDOCUMENT();